The IMF needs more Lagarde.
Davos - Lagarde once said, she has an open mind to serving another five years as the managing director of the International Monetary Fund (IMF).
She should stay on.
The IMF has never had a better leadership team than hers, and the IMF Board should give her the chance to complete the work she has started.
Lagarde took office in July 2011, inheriting a crisis-ridden institution.
The 2008 global financial collapse and its subsequent economic aftershocks completely discredited Western-led multilateral lending institutions and the "Washington Consensus" of free markets.
Lagarde's leadership helped the IMF regain its reputation.
Many eyes are turned to her personal qualities — — as they should be.
She is candid, forceful, warm, and moving.
Diplomats from various countries who met her (often in subtle settings) all praised her for daring to speak of difficult realities while also being a sensitive listener.
For a leader of an institution that must negotiate terms rather than dictate everything, these are important qualities.
Merkel told Europeans that their banks needed restructuring, or else they had to build a firewall to prevent financial contagion.
Similarly, she is loudly calling on some countries to provide IMF support — such as Greece, Pakistan, Tunisia, and Ukraine — which is crucial for global stability.
There are countless examples.
The IMF is not good at innovation, nor is it usually passionate about it.
Lagarde started changing this.
During this process, she gave this institution, which usually prescribes bitter medicines, a humane face.
For instance, helping to manage the Middle East refugee crisis was not originally within the IMF's mandate.
However, under her leadership, the IMF adjusted its plan, allowing the Jordanian government to use more funds to help those displaced by the Syrian and Iraqi conflicts, more than one million of whom were living in refugee camps within Jordan.
Similarly, in 2014, when the Ebola outbreak occurred in West Africa, Lagarde led the IMF to use its usable funds to grant debt relief to countries in the crisis, enabling them to raise doctors' and nurses' allowances – this was the IMF's first such use of its own capital.
In addition, Lagarde recognizes that the world today faces three major challenges and has taken action on them.
First, she assertively demanded that more women join the labor force, and she herself served as a model for the value of women holding leadership positions.
Across a range of countries from Saudi Arabia to Japan, she urged leaders to stop squandering such vast human resources – and achieve economic potential with them.
In addition, under her leadership, the IMF also addressed the broader issue of income inequality.
This is not just a basic issue of fairness.
Research by the IMF emphasizes a direct link between reducing income inequality and promoting economic growth.
The IMF is not the first institution to prove this point, but its position makes this issue stand out and become more urgent.
Lagarde has long focused on highlighting this point, which is a key factor in its urgency.
Thirdly, Lagadec played a major role in helping the world to be aware of the impact of technological change - some of which will have disastrous consequences.
For example, automation will continue to improve the efficiency and reduce the cost of manufacturing, but it also means that the number of jobs created by economic growth is not as much as before.
The political, economic, and social implications of this emerging reality are worth our recognition and serious study.
Lagarde made the IMF the core of this work.
Critics say it's time for developing countries to take the lead in the IMF.
Ultimately, Lagarde has been the 11th European to hold the position, and Europe's privileged status in the world is becoming increasingly hard to justify.
Some people say that the austerity measures supported by the IMF have not had a full impact on Greece, which indicates that she has lost touch with the general public.
Some have pointed out that she faces charges linked to a financial scandal in France, which would distract her from her work at the IMF.
Following her predecessor Dominique Strauss-Kahn's involvement in scandal, critics felt the IMF could not afford to be distracted yet again by a similar incident.
Let's analyze these opposing views one by one.
The IMF (and the World Bank) should welcome leaders from outside Europe and the US.
The purpose of ending this Western privilege is to base the selection process of leaders on merit rather than political considerations.
Lagarde is the best candidate for IMF president, and the emerging powers, including the BRIC countries (Brazil, Russia, India and China), have not jointly endorsed any alternative candidate.
Having an European head of the IMF may also be one of the factors that contributed to the IMF's decision to include the renminbi in the basket of currencies that determines the value of its special drawing rights last year.
In addition, Lagarde won over the US Congress's Republicans and Democrats with impressive political flexibility, ultimately convincing them to approve IMF governance reforms that not only strengthened IMF's ability to contain financial crises, but also more accurately reflected the evolving global economic dynamics.
For example, the BRICS countries have already entered the top ten shareholders of the IMF.
On the issue of Greece, Lagarde made some comments last year that were quite characteristic of her style, but not everyone thought they were suitable.
But she was not the one who brought economic hardship to the Greeks, she has shown in her tenure at the IMF that in IMF history, there has been no managing director who has done as much as she has to lead IMF efforts to alleviate the suffering of the people in a crisis.
Finally, the allegations against Lagarde were opposed by the French prosecutor general, and Lagarde was at most only slightly implicated.
The world urgently needs a leader who is committed to making the world a safer and more prosperous place.
Lagarde has proven herself to be the kind of leader who is committed to making the IMF relevant in the 21st century.
She deserves a fair chance from the start.
